1. Find a Project
Use platforms like GitHub Explore or Good First Issue to find beginner-friendly projects.

Look for repositories with clear documentation and open issues labeled like good first issue, help wanted, etc.

2. Fork the Repository
Go to the projectâ€™s GitHub page.

Click the Fork button at the top-right to create a personal copy of the repository under your account.

3. Clone the Forked Repository
Open your terminal or Git Bash.

Run:

bash
Copy
Edit
git clone https://github.com/your-username/repo-name.git
This creates a local copy of your fork on your computer.

4. Create a New Branch
Navigate into the project folder:

bash
Copy
Edit
cd repo-name
Create and switch to a new branch:

bash
Copy
Edit
git checkout -b feature-branch-name
5. Make Your Changes
Edit the code, fix bugs, or add new features using your favorite editor.

Be sure to follow the projectâ€™s contribution guidelines (usually in CONTRIBUTING.md).

6. Stage and Commit Your Changes
Stage your changes:

bash
Copy
Edit
git add .
Commit with a meaningful message:

bash
Copy
Edit
git commit -m "Add feature/fix bug: brief description"
7. Push Changes to Your Fork
Push the branch to your GitHub fork:

bash
Copy
Edit
git push origin feature-branch-name
8. Open a Pull Request (PR)
Go to your forked repo on GitHub.

Click "Compare & pull request".

Add a clear title and description of your changes.

Submit the pull request to the original repositoryâ€™s main or development branch.

9. Collaborate and Respond to Feedback
Project maintainers may review your code and request changes.

Update your code and push again â€” your PR will be automatically updated.

